  "What is torque?": "",
  "The product of mass and angular velocity": "",
  "The resistance of a body to angular acceleration": "",
  "The rate of change of angular momentum over distance": "",
  "The rotational analog of force; the tendency of a force to cause rotation about an axis": "",
  "Torque is the rotational analog of force. It measures how effectively a force causes rotation about an axis, calculated as τ = r × F.": "",
  "What does 'moment arm' (lever arm) mean?": "",
  "The length of the object being rotated": "",
  "The perpendicular distance from the axis of rotation to the line of action of the force": "",
  "The distance from the center of mass to the axis of rotation": "",
  "The radius of the circular path": "",
  "The moment arm (lever arm) is the perpendicular distance from the rotation axis to the line of action of the force. Torque equals force times moment arm.": "",
  "What is Newton's Second Law for rotation?": "",
  "L = Iω for constant angular momentum": "",
  "F = ma applied to circular motion": "",
  "τ_net = Iα; net torque equals moment of inertia times angular acceleration": "",
  "τ = mr²ω": "",
  "Newton's Second Law for rotation states τ_net = Iα. It is the rotational analog of F_net = ma.": "",
  "What is static rotational equilibrium?": "",
  "A state where the net torque about any axis is zero and the object does not rotate": "",
  "A state where all forces are balanced but torques are not": "",
  "A state where angular momentum is conserved": "",
  "A state where the object spins at constant angular velocity": "",
  "Static rotational equilibrium means the net torque about any axis is zero (Στ = 0) and the object has no angular acceleration.": "",
  "What is a couple in mechanics?": "",
